   liquefaction of biomass: Comprehensive experiment and prediction of
   various product fraction yields},
Journal = {ENERGY CONVERSION AND MANAGEMENT},
Year = {2023},
Volume = {292},
Month = {SEP 15},
Abstract = {Hydrothermal liquefaction (HTL) shows promise in biocrude productions
   from wet biomass. In this study, phycocyanin conversion was performed
   under an extensive range of conditions (set-point temperatures of
   300-500 degrees C and holding times of 20-1800 s), covering both
   isothermal and fast HTL processes. Based on 226 sets of product fraction
   yields obtained from this study and literature, machine learning models,
   such as multiple linear regression, decision regression tree, random
   forest, gradient boosting regression, and support vector regression were
   developed. The model with the highest predictive accuracy for biocrude
   yield was further used to perform both single and multi-task predictions
   of other product yields. The results show that fast HTL at 500 degrees C
   and 40 s produced the highest biocrude yield (35.0 wt\%) and energy
   recovery (55.2\%), which were 11.9 wt\% and 15.9\% higher than those
   obtained by conventional isothermal HTL at 300 degrees C and 1800 s.
   Biocrude predominantly consisted of nitrogenous heterocyclic compounds,
   leading to its high nitrogen content (similar to 10 wt\%). In addition,
   water quality analysis shows that the chemical oxygen demand, ammonia
   and total phosphorus contents of the aqueous phase by-products were much
   higher than the discharge standards and required further treatments.
   Cross-validation and testing error analysis show that the random forest
   model exhibited the highest predictive accuracy for the biocrude yield,
   with a testing R-2 of 0.93. Additionally, the random forest model could
   predict other product fraction yields with desirable accuracies.
   According to the feature importance analysis, the most important factor
   for biocrude production from fast HTL was the residence time, followed
   by the reaction temperature.},
Type = {Article},
Affiliation = {Wang, S (Corresponding Author), Jiangsu Univ, Sch Energy \& Power Engn, Zhenjiang 212013, Jiangsu, Peoples R China.
